Anonymous Fri 30 Sep 2022 03:10:34 No.51295013 Report
Quoted By: >>51295077 >>51295651
>>51293633
Being the type that prefers to write (or mostly finish) everything, you get a much tighter result by not going chapter-by-chapter. No matter how much you plan, there will be times that you have to heavily revise earlier material.
On the other hand, nearly all the stories here don't require that much attention to foreshadowing, hidden clues, or other details. What will kill a story faster than painting yourself in a corner is consistency in quantity and quality of details. If you're not used to huge worldbuilding, such as with the longer OP stories that aren't SoL settings, then make a few general guidelines and keep your scale small and simple. Let characters react to each other and the action.
On the gripping hand, better is a relative term. Someone that is not actively writing and enjoys Story XYZ is going to have a very different opinion on what suits your story than a fan of Story ABC, and the same for active writers. I try to be very non-judgmental when talking shop, but even then I'm not completely impartial.

Just get something down. That's always the second step.
The first is believing in your characters.
All the rest is showing up to work each day and making progress.

>>51295077
You missed the first portion of what I said.
My first, and sometimes second, drafts are for me alone. Then I do a complete readthrough, check for continuity errors (house layouts, for example), and then do a grammar check.
After a second readthrough, only then do I feel it's ready for a first/beta reader. At that point, I'm looking for what I missed in tone and pace. The huge revisions happened months before. Maybe it was a missing conversation or whole chapters.
So for me, the first edition is my drafts, the second is here, and anything else is in print.

On the other hand, I have a piece that I'm revising that's two years old. I need it and others to fit details from a much longer story. That also fits what I meant.
But expecting the average writer here to have two editions? No. Correct the grammar you missed and move on. A story is not a 100% completion achievement.

>>51295651
The only thing that gets easier is knowing you've done it before.
Take it scene by scene and chapter by chapter. If it's your first, it's both hard work and fun. Have fun on the adventure.
